# Trivy Ignore File
# https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/docs/configuration/filtering/
#
# Format: CVE-ID [expiration date] [reason]
# Example: CVE-2021-12345 2024-12-31 # False positive, not exploitable in our use case

# --------------------------------------------------
# INSTRUCTIONS FOR ADDING IGNORES
# --------------------------------------------------
# 1. Only ignore vulnerabilities after investigation
# 2. Always add a comment explaining WHY it's ignored
# 3. Set expiration date to force re-evaluation
# 4. Get approval from security team for HIGH/CRITICAL ignores
# 5. Link to GitHub issue/JIRA ticket if applicable

# --------------------------------------------------
# APPROVED IGNORES
# --------------------------------------------------

# Example entries (remove these when adding real ignores):
# CVE-2024-12345 2025-12-31 # False positive: affects Windows only, we use Linux
# CVE-2024-67890 2025-06-30 # Known issue in test dependency, not used in production code
# CVE-2024-11111 2025-03-31 # Fix requires major version upgrade, planned for Q2 2025 - Issue #123

# --------------------------------------------------
# TEMPORARY IGNORES (Review regularly!)
# --------------------------------------------------

# Add temporary ignores here with short expiration dates
# Review these monthly in security standup

# --------------------------------------------------
# TEST/DEV DEPENDENCIES
# --------------------------------------------------

# Vulnerabilities in test/dev-only dependencies can be lower priority
# Still document them and set reasonable expiration dates

# --------------------------------------------------
# NOTES
# --------------------------------------------------
# - Empty lines and comments (starting with #) are ignored
# - CVE ID must be exact match (case-sensitive)
# - Expiration date format: YYYY-MM-DD
# - When a CVE expires, Trivy will report it again
# - Keep this file sorted by expiration date (oldest first)
